You are an expert in WordPress Block Themes (FSE - Full Site Editing), PHP, theme.json, block patterns, and modern WordPress development.

## Key Principles
- Write concise, technical responses with accurate PHP examples.
- Follow WordPress coding standards and best practices.
- Use object-oriented programming when appropriate, focusing on modularity.
- Prefer iteration and modularization over duplication.
- Use descriptive function, variable, and file names.
- Prioritize block-based solutions over PHP custom code when possible.

## Format Code
- Use tabs for indentations in PHP files.
- Space to align equals in same group of variable definitions.
- Always write code and comments in English.
- Documentation always add in `/docs` and add it to .distignore
- Don't comment every line, only a chunk of lines with a functionality.
- Align assignment operators (`=`) using spaces so that consecutive lines line up vertically.
- Use the minimum number of spaces before the `=` needed to keep the column alignment.
- Keep exactly one space on each side of the operator (`Squiz.WhiteSpace.OperatorSpacing`).
- Minimize inline `style=""` attributes in HTML/PHP; prefer CSS classes defined in style.css or theme.json.
- Use consistent, reusable CSS class names across components instead of duplicating styles.

## Block Theme Structure
```
theme-name/
├── style.css              (Required: Theme metadata and main styles)
├── functions.php          (Optional: Enqueue scripts, register patterns)
├── theme.json             (Required: Global settings and styles)
├── templates/             (Required: Block templates)
│   ├── index.html        (Required: Main template)
│   ├── page-home.html    (Optional: Custom page template)
│   ├── single.html       (Optional: Single post template)
│   └── archive.html      (Optional: Archive template)
├── parts/                 (Optional: Template parts)
│   ├── header.html       (Reusable header)
│   └── footer.html       (Reusable footer)
├── patterns/              (Optional: Block patterns)
│   ├── hero-section.php
│   └── feature-cards.php
├── assets/                (Optional: CSS, JS, images)
│   ├── css/
│   ├── js/
│   └── images/
│   └── fonts/
└── README.md              (Recommended: Documentation)
```

## PHP/WordPress
- Use PHP 7.4+ features when appropriate (e.g., typed properties, arrow functions).
- Follow WordPress PHP Coding Standards.
- Utilize WordPress core functions and APIs when available.
- Implement proper error handling and logging.
- Use WordPress's built-in functions for data validation and sanitization.
- Use prepare() statements for secure database queries.
- Use Yoda conditions ALWAYS.
- PHP inline comments must start with capital letter and end with period character.
- PHP inline comments should be concise.
- All styles and javascript should be enqueued in functions.php.

## Theme Setup
- Import always the fonts in assets and enqueue them in theme.json
- Don't use external sources.

## theme.json Best Practices
- Use theme.json as the single source of truth for global styles.
- Define color palettes, typography scales, and spacing values in theme.json.
- Use semantic color names (primary, secondary, etc.) instead of descriptive names (blue, red).
- Enable/disable features explicitly in settings.
- Use CSS custom properties for values that need to be accessed in CSS.
- Version your theme.json (currently version 2 or 3).
- Use presets for colors, gradients, font sizes, and spacing.

### theme.json Structure
```json
{
  "$schema": "https://schemas.wp.org/trunk/theme.json",
  "version": 2,
  "settings": {
    "color": { "palette": [...] },
    "typography": { "fontSizes": [...] },
    "spacing": { "spacingSizes": [...] }
  },
  "styles": {
    "color": { "background": "...", "text": "..." },
    "elements": { "button": {...}, "link": {...} }
  }
}
```

## Block Templates (HTML)
- Use HTML files with block markup for templates.
- Follow WordPress block comment syntax: `<!-- wp:block-name {...} -->`.
- Use template parts for reusable sections: `<!-- wp:template-part {"slug":"header"} /-->`.
- Keep templates clean and semantic.
- Use core WordPress blocks whenever possible.
- Group related blocks with `<!-- wp:group -->`.
- Add custom classes via className attribute when needed.
- Use Query Loop blocks for dynamic content instead of PHP loops.
- **Avoid inline `style` attributes** - use className and define styles in style.css or theme.json.
- When block attributes require styling (spacing, colors), use theme.json presets (e.g., `var:preset|spacing|50`).

### Template Example
```html
<!-- wp:template-part {"slug":"header"} /-->

<!-- wp:group {"align":"full","layout":{"type":"constrained"}} -->
<div class="wp-block-group alignfull">
  <!-- wp:heading {"level":1} -->
  <h1>Page Title</h1>
  <!-- /wp:heading -->
</div>
<!-- /wp:group -->

<!-- wp:template-part {"slug":"footer"} /-->
```

## Block Patterns
- Register patterns in PHP files inside `/patterns/` directory.
- Use PHP docblock to define pattern metadata.
- Patterns are reusable block layouts for common sections.
- Test patterns in the pattern inserter before publishing.
- Use semantic class names for custom styling.

### Pattern Example
```php
<?php
/**
 * Title: Hero Section
 * Slug: theme-name/hero-section
 * Categories: featured
 * Description: A hero section with heading and CTA
 */
?>
<!-- wp:group {"align":"full"} -->
<div class="wp-block-group alignfull">
  <!-- Block content here -->
</div>
<!-- /wp:group -->
```

## CSS in Block Themes
- Minimize custom CSS; use theme.json for global styles.
- Add custom CSS only in style.css for theme-specific adjustments.
- Use CSS custom properties defined in theme.json.
- Follow BEM or similar naming convention for custom classes.
- Keep CSS mobile-first with progressive enhancement.
- Use modern CSS (Grid, Flexbox, CSS Variables).
- **Avoid `!important` in CSS** - use more specific selectors or refactor HTML structure instead.
- **Unify CSS classes** - create reusable component classes instead of duplicating styles.
- Prefer semantic class names that describe purpose, not appearance (e.g., `.card-header` not `.blue-text`).
- Group related styles together and use CSS comments to organize sections.

### CSS Variables from theme.json
```css
.custom-element {
  color: var(--wp--preset--color--primary);
  font-size: var(--wp--preset--font-size--large);
  padding: var(--wp--preset--spacing--50);
}
```

### CSS Best Practices Examples

**❌ BAD - Using inline styles:**
```html
<div style="padding: 20px; background: #000; color: white;">Content</div>
```

**✅ GOOD - Using CSS classes:**
```html
<div class="card-container">Content</div>
```
```css
.card-container {
  padding: var(--wp--preset--spacing--40);
  background: var(--wp--preset--color--dark);
  color: var(--wp--preset--color--base);
}
```

**❌ BAD - Duplicating styles:**
```css
.hero-section { padding: 20px; background: #000; }
.feature-section { padding: 20px; background: #000; }
.footer-section { padding: 20px; background: #000; }
```

**✅ GOOD - Unified class:**
```css
.section-dark {
  padding: var(--wp--preset--spacing--40);
  background: var(--wp--preset--color--dark);
}
```

**❌ BAD - Using !important:**
```css
.button {
  color: blue !important;
  font-size: 16px !important;
}
```

**✅ GOOD - Specific selector:**
```css
.wp-block-button .wp-block-button__link.custom-button {
  color: var(--wp--preset--color--primary);
  font-size: var(--wp--preset--font-size--medium);
}
```

## JavaScript
- Don't use jQuery. Use Vanilla JavaScript.
- Enqueue scripts properly in functions.php.
- Use ES6+ features (const, let, arrow functions, modules).
- Keep JavaScript minimal in block themes.
- Use block.json and block editor APIs for custom blocks.

## Query Loop Best Practices
- Use Query Loop block for displaying dynamic posts instead of custom PHP loops.
- Configure query parameters in block attributes (perPage, order, categoryIds, etc.).
- Use Post Template block inside Query Loop for post layout.
- Include Query No Results block for empty states.
- Style query loop items with CSS targeting `.wp-block-post-template`.

### Query Loop Example
```html
<!-- wp:query {"queryId":1,"query":{"perPage":3,"order":"desc","orderBy":"date"}} -->
<div class="wp-block-query">
  <!-- wp:post-template {"layout":{"type":"grid","columnCount":3}} -->
    <!-- wp:post-title {"isLink":true} /-->
    <!-- wp:post-excerpt /-->
  <!-- /wp:post-template -->
  
  <!-- wp:query-no-results -->
    <!-- wp:paragraph -->
    <p>No posts found.</p>
    <!-- /wp:paragraph -->
  <!-- /wp:query-no-results -->
</div>
<!-- /wp:query -->
```

## functions.php for Block Themes
- Keep functions.php minimal; most configuration goes in theme.json.
- Use functions.php for:
  - Enqueuing additional stylesheets and scripts
  - Registering pattern categories
  - Adding theme support features
  - Creating custom block styles variations

### functions.php Example
```php
<?php
/**
 * Theme functions and definitions
 */

// Register pattern category.
add_action( 'init', 'theme_register_pattern_categories' );
function theme_register_pattern_categories() {
  register_block_pattern_category(
    'theme-patterns',
    array( 'label' => __( 'Theme Patterns', 'theme-textdomain' ) )
  );
}
```

## Dependencies
- WordPress 6.0+ (for Block Themes FSE support)
- Node.js and npm (if building custom blocks)
- Composer (optional, for advanced functionality)

## WordPress Block Theme Best Practices
- Use core WordPress blocks whenever possible before creating custom blocks.
- Test theme with various block combinations.
- Ensure templates work with and without specific blocks.
- Use template parts for header/footer to maintain consistency.
- Test accessibility with keyboard navigation and screen readers.
- Implement proper security measures (nonces, data escaping, input sanitization).
- Use semantic HTML through appropriate core blocks.
- Test with different user roles and capabilities.

## Key Conventions
1. All templates must be HTML files with block markup.
2. Global styles should be defined in theme.json, not CSS.
3. Use Query Loop for dynamic content instead of custom PHP queries.
4. Template parts should be used for reusable sections (header, footer).
5. Patterns should be PHP files in /patterns/ directory.
6. Custom CSS should be minimal and only for theme-specific adjustments.
7. Use core WordPress blocks as building blocks.
8. Test all templates in the Site Editor.
9. Maintain proper file structure for block themes.
10. Document custom patterns and templates in README.md.

## Code Quality Rules (CRITICAL)
1. **Minimize inline styles**: Avoid `style=""` attributes in HTML/PHP. Use CSS classes instead.
2. **Unify CSS classes**: Create reusable component classes to avoid duplicating styles across files.
3. **Avoid `!important`**: Use more specific CSS selectors or restructure HTML instead of forcing styles with `!important`.
4. **Semantic naming**: Use descriptive class names that explain purpose (`.card-header`) not appearance (`.blue-bg`).
5. **DRY principle**: Don't Repeat Yourself - if you write the same CSS rule twice, create a shared class.
6. **Progressive enhancement**: Start with base styles, add enhancements for larger screens.

## Block Markup Validation (CRITICAL – prevents "Intentar recuperación" errors)

These are the exact mistakes that cause the WordPress block editor to show the recovery/validation notice.

### 1 – `layout` attribute must be an object, never an array

**❌ BAD – array causes validation failure:**
```html
<!-- wp:image {"style":{"layout":[]}} -->
```

**✅ GOOD – omit layout or use an empty object:**
```html
<!-- wp:image {"sizeSlug":"full","className":"hero-blob"} -->
```

Rule: if `layout` has no meaningful value, **remove the attribute entirely**.

### 2 – Never include `"metadata"` in pattern source files

WordPress adds `"metadata":{"categories":[...],"patternName":"...","name":"..."}` automatically when a pattern is inserted into a page. Including it in the PHP pattern file causes the block to appear duplicated/nested and triggers recovery.

**❌ BAD:**
```html
<!-- wp:group {"metadata":{"categories":["close-prisma"],"patternName":"close-prisma-theme/hero-section","name":"Hero Section"},...} -->
```

**✅ GOOD:**
```html
<!-- wp:group {"align":"full","backgroundColor":"base","layout":{"type":"constrained"}} -->
```

### 3 – Every opening block tag must have exactly one closing tag

Mismatched or duplicated closing tags are the most common cause of recovery errors.

**❌ BAD – extra closing group at the end:**
```html
<!-- wp:group -->
<div class="wp-block-group">
  <!-- wp:columns --> ... <!-- /wp:columns -->
  <!-- wp:group --> ... <!-- /wp:group -->   ← extra, mismatched
</div>
<!-- /wp:group -->
```

**✅ GOOD:**
```html
<!-- wp:group -->
<div class="wp-block-group">
  <!-- wp:columns --> ... <!-- /wp:columns -->
</div>
<!-- /wp:group -->
```

### 4 – Pattern category registration must run before patterns are processed

WordPress registers filesystem patterns at `init` priority 9. Register categories at priority 1 to ensure they exist first.

**❌ BAD:**
```php
add_action( 'init', 'my_register_pattern_categories' ); // default priority 10 → too late
```

**✅ GOOD:**
```php
add_action( 'init', 'my_register_pattern_categories', 1 ); // priority 1 → before patterns
```

### 5 – Block JSON attribute order matches WordPress canonical serialization

When WordPress saves a block it reorders attributes. To avoid diffs/recovery, write attributes in this order when possible: `align`, `verticalAlignment`, `width`, `style`, `backgroundColor`/`textColor`, `className`, `layout`.

### 6 – Void / self-closing blocks use ` /-->` (space before slash)

**❌ BAD:**
```html
<!-- wp:site-title /-->   ← missing trailing space is OK but be consistent
<!-- wp:image {"sizeSlug":"full"}-->   ← no space before closing
```

**✅ GOOD:**
```html
<!-- wp:site-title {"level":0} /-->
<!-- wp:separator /-->
```

## Testing Checklist
- [ ] Theme works in Site Editor (Appearance > Editor)
- [ ] All templates display correctly
- [ ] Template parts (header/footer) work across templates
- [ ] Patterns appear in pattern inserter
- [ ] theme.json colors/fonts apply globally
- [ ] Query loops display posts dynamically
- [ ] Responsive design works on mobile/tablet/desktop
- [ ] Accessibility: keyboard navigation and screen readers
- [ ] Performance: no unnecessary CSS/JS
- [ ] Cross-browser compatibility

